# Webgoose - Web 1.0 Style, Static Site Generator 

---

## In Development:

This software does **NOT** currently support all of the functions listed in this document. This functionality will (hopefully) be available upon the release of v1.0.0.

The information noted here may not be representative of the final software, and only serves to detail the current direction of development. 

The information and the API(s) documented here may change at any time.

---


Webgoose is a Static Site Generator designed for Small, Web 1.0 Style Sites. Webgoose doesn't care for Front-End Frameworks, SCSS, Posts, Pagination, or anything like that; only the content, templates, and config.

Webgoose uses Markdown or HTML with YAML Frontmatter, and makes use of the Jinja2 Templating Engine and CMARK-GFM to render pages.


## Installation:

Webgoose can be installed by running the following commands:

```
git clone https://github.com/jeff0282/webgoose
cd webgoose
pip3 install .
```


## Usage:
**[Not Yet Supported]**

``webgoose build`` - The Command To Build The Site in the Current Directory

``webgoose init`` - Initialise a Site in the Current Directory with Defaults (see *"Recommended Site Structure"* in the *"Quick Start"* section)

Other commands may be added in the future!


## The Quick Start !!

A (kind of) Quick Intro to making sites with Webgoose!

The ``webgoose init`` command sets up a site with default values that should "just work", allowing you to get started on writing your pages and templates right away!

### Recommended Site Structure:

Below is the recommended directory structure for Webgoose sites, and is the structure set up by the `webgoose init` command by default.

In this recommended config, the **Build Directory** is set to ".", so that the built site is output in the root directory of the site (in this case the `example-site` directory)

```
# EXTRACT FROM DEFAULT 'config.yaml'
	
source_dir: ".source"
build_dir: "."
template_dir: ".template"
default_template: "default.html"


# EXAMPLE SITE FOLLOWING ABOVE CONFIG
│
| example-site/
│
├── .config/
│   └── style.css
│
├── .source/
│    ├── index.md
│    ├── about.md
│    └── static/
│        ├── style.css
│        └── image.jpg
│
└── .template/
	├── default.html
	└── homepage.html
```

**NOTE:** With this configuration, it is **STRONGLY** recommended to set up your Web Server to **NOT** serve hidden files or directories.


### Writing Pages:

With Webgoose, pages are Markdown Files with YAML Frontmatter.

```
---
title: Example Page
description: An Example Page Showing The Basic Layout
---

Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Ut condimentum et ante in bibendum. Aenean lobortis lorem aliquet tempus mattis. Pellentesque rhoncus rhoncus velit, eget aliquet nibh rhoncus in. Pellentesque mattis enim a purus convallis accumsan. Nam nec lectus ac orci dapibus vulputate. 
```

In order for these files to be picked up, they must be ".md" files and be placed inside the **Source Directory** (`.source` by default).

HTML inside of the Page Content is also valid, for example.

```
---
title: A Page With Both Markdown and HTML
---

# This is a header

### This is another, smaller header

<div class="img-card">
	<img src="/static/res/example.jpg">
	<div>
		This is some text
	</div>
</div>
```

Webgoose also supports options to disable Markdown conversion on select pages, these options are covered in the *"Page Metadata"* Section.

However, this is **NOT** valid, as Markdown headers must be placed at the start of a line, with no preceding whitespace.

```
---
title: A Page With Both Markdown and HTML
---

<div class="img-card">
	<img src="/static/res/example.jpg">
	<div>
		# This Is An Invalid Markdown Header

		The above header will not be picked up by the Markdown Conversion
	</div>
</div>
```


