## The Build Process:
**[Not Yet Fully Implemented]**

When the ``webgoose build`` command is run, Webgoose begins the three stages of the build process:

- Check
- Load
- Render & Output


### 'Check' Stage:

Before Webgoose builds anything, it'll first check that all is good-to-go.

Webgoose will attempt to locate a config file at (in descending order):

- ``.config/config.yaml``
- ``.config.yaml``

Failure to find a config file is considered a **Fatal Error**.

If a config file is found, Webgoose will check it for errors, add default values as required.

Should the config be valid, the source, build, and other directories will be tested to see if they exist.

Any errors encountered during these checks is considered **Fatal**.


### 'Load' Stage:

The Bread and Butter or Webgoose !!

Using the config file, Webgoose will look inside the **Source Directory** and recursively retrieve all (non-hidden) files.

An Abstract Directory Tree will then be constructed representing the final structure of the site. The tree will contain File and Page objects housing their relevant information. The completed tree will be used to complete the build process, and will be provided to the user in template and page files.

Any errors encountered during this stage is considered **Fatal**.


### 'Render & Output' Stage:

At this stage, Webgoose will traverse the completed Abstract Directory Tree, rendering all pages found, and copying/outputting all files & rendered pages to their respective location in the **Build Directory**. The structure of the final site will respect the structure inside the **Source Directory**.

Pages are rendered as follows:

- Page Content is evaluated using Jinja2,
- Page Content is passed through Markdown-to-HTML converter (unless stated otherwise)
- Template is loaded and evaluated using Jinja2, with the evaluated page content being passed as a variable

As a result of this, variables declared inside the template cannot be accessed inside the page file, and vice-versa.

Errors related to syntax errors in Templates and Page Files are considered **Non-Fatal**, and will result in the Page being skipped.

Any other errors are considered **Fatal**.
